  "preFix": {
    "title": "Battered sausage",
    "subtitle": "A pork sausage in crisp chip shop batter, deep-fried at home",
    "excerpt": "The battered sausage is the chip shop staple that sits alongside fish and chips. A pre-cooked pork sausage dipped in a simple batter and deep-fried until the coating is pale gold and crisp. Made at home, it is better than any takeaway version.",
    "sourceNotes": "British chip shop staple. Battered sausages have been sold in fish and chip shops since at least the early 20th century, particularly in the North of England and Scotland. The batter is the same used for fish, applied to a pre-cooked pork sausage.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "The battered sausage needs to be cooked before battering. Frying raw sausage in batter risks the centre staying cold while the coating overcooks. Cook the sausages gently on the hob first, cool them, then dip them in batter and fry. The batter should be just thick enough to coat: it should fall from a spoon in a slow, steady drip. The oil temperature matters: 180°C is the target.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "infoPanel",
          "attrs": {
            "body": "Use a deep, heavy-based pan and fill it no more than one-third full with oil. Keep a lid or damp cloth nearby. Never leave hot oil unattended, and never add wet food directly to the oil without patting it dry first. An instant-read thermometer is essential for accurate temperature control.",
            "title": "Deep frying safely"
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
